        <div xml:id="AN1-kilavi"></div>
        <div xml:id="AN1">
            <lg type="edition"><l>vaṇṭupaṭat tatainta kaṇṇi yoṇkaḻa</l>
<l>luruvak kutirai maḻava rōṭṭiya</l>
<l>muruka ṉaṟpōr neṭuvē ḷāvi</l>
<l>yaṟukōṭ ṭiyāṉaip <choice><seg>potuḷiya</seg><seg>potiṉi</seg></choice> yāṅkaṭ</l>
<l>ciṟukā rōṭaṉ payiṉoṭu cērttiya</l>
<l>kaṟpōṟ piriyala meṉṟa coṟṟā</l>
<l>maṟantaṉar kollō tōḻi ciṟanta</l>
<l>vēymaruḷ <choice><seg>paṇaittō</seg><seg>paṇaittōḷ</seg></choice> <choice><seg>ṇekiḻac</seg><seg>ñekiḻa</seg></choice> <choice><seg>cēeynāṭṭup</seg><seg>nāṭṭup</seg></choice></l>
<l>polaṅkala veṟukkai tarumār nilampaka</l>
<l>vaḻalpōl veṅkatir paitaṟat teṟutali</l>
<l>ṉiḻaṟēyn tulaṟiya maratta <choice><seg>varaikāy</seg><seg>vaṟaikāy</seg></choice></l>
<l>paṟunīrp paiñcuṉai yāmaṟap pulartali</l>
<l>ṉukuneṟ poriyum vemmaiya yāvarum</l>
<l>vaḻaṅkuna riṉmaiyiṉ <choice><seg>vauvunar</seg><seg>vavvunar</seg></choice> maṭiyac</l>
<l>curampul leṉṟa vāṟṟa valaṅkuciṉai</l>
<l><choice><seg>nāriṉ</seg><seg>nārila</seg></choice> muruṅkai <choice><seg>naviral</seg><seg>virala</seg></choice> vāṉpūc</l>
<l>cūralaṅ kaṭuvaḷi yeṭuppa vāruṟ</l>
<l>ṟuṭaitiraip pitirviṟ poṅkimuṉ</l>
<l>kaṭalpō ṟōṉṟala kāṭiṟan tōrē.</l></lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l rend="indent">	In that place <choice><seg>full of </seg><seg>Potiṉi, with </seg></choice> the elephants with broken tusks</l>
<l rend="indent">	of Āvi with long rule in good battle, [and] of Murukaṉ,<note place="foot">Syntax is unmarked here, but the most plausible construction is a genitive relation between the place (Potiṉi or simply āṅkaṇ) and both Āvi and Murukaṉ, and that Murukaṉ was thought to have intervened in one of Āvi’s battles.</note></l>
<l rend="indent">	who made warriors with shapely horses run,</l>
<l rend="indent">	bright anklets [and] chaplets dense so that bees settle [there],</l>
<l>the words “we won’t separate, like the stones</l>
<l rend="indent">	joined together with glue by the little whetstone maker”,</l>
<l>has he forgotten [them], friend,</l>
<l>– he who,</l>
<l>in order to bring a wealth of golden <choice><seg>ornaments, </seg><seg>ornaments </seg></choice> from strange lands,</l>
<l rend="indent">	while [my] superb bamboo-like bamboo shoulders become emaciated,</l>
<l rend="indent">	traversed wildernesses that appear like the sea</l>
<l rend="indent">	before [him], foaming with the spray of breaking waves,</l>
<l rend="indent">	roaring when the whirling fierce wind lifts</l>
<l rend="indent">	the <choice><seg>dishevelled </seg><seg>fingery </seg></choice> pure flowers of barkless <choice><seg>Muruṅkai</seg><seg>Muruṅkai trees</seg></choice> </l>
<l rend="indent">	with swaying branches on empty desert paths,</l>
<l rend="indent">	where robbers doze, in the absence of anybody passing,</l>
<l rend="indent">	in the heat that parches the paddy shed because of drying up,</l>
<l rend="indent">	while the water ceases in mountain pools with ceasing water,</l>
<l rend="indent">	the rocks with withering trees sweltering, shade dwindling,</l>
<l rend="indent">	because [sun] beams hot like fire scorch, so that the green ceases,</l>
<l rend="indent">	so that the ground cracks.</l></lg>
        </div>
    </body>
